<blockquote>
<p><strong>Hi there</strong>! This post is <a href="/series/">part of a series</a> I am doing where I attempt to move most of the applications I use at home over to Linux. If you find this interesting you may enjoy the other posts too!</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Today I will be covering getting up and running with <a href="https://nodered.org/">Node-RED</a> on your server. This process is slightly more involved compared to all the previous installs we have done so far, however this post aims to make it as simple as possible!</p>
<h2 id="installing-nodejs">Installing Node.js</h2>
<p>In order to run Node-RED you will need to have <a href="https://nodejs.org/en/">Node.js</a> installed, these steps are a condensed version of the <a href="https://github.com/nodesource/distributions/blob/master/README.md#debinstall">official installation guide</a> for Ubuntu.</p>
<p>To install Node.js 12.x simply run the below command on your server:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
curl -sL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_12.x | sudo -E bash -
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Once complete you can install Node.js using the following command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo apt-get install -y nodejs
{% endhighlight %}

<p>You can run the below command to verify that the installation succeeded:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
npm --version && node --version
{% endhighlight %}

<p>You should see output similar to the below:</p>
<img src="./001.png" alt="" />
<h2 id="installing-node-red">Installing Node-RED</h2>
<p>Once we have Node.js installed we can move on to installing Node-RED, the below commands are taken from the <a href="https://nodered.org/docs/getting-started/local">official documentation</a>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Note</strong>: you will need to run most of these commands as <code>sudo</code></p>
</blockquote>
<p>You can install Node-RED with the below command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo npm install -g --unsafe-perm node-red
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Once installed, you can test that everything is working by launching Node-RED with it's default settings:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
node-red
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Once Node-RED has started you should be able to access it on your server's IP Address on port 1880 in my case that would be http://10.0.0.53:1880.</p>
<img src="./002.png" alt="" />
<h2 id="securing-node-red">Securing Node-RED</h2>
<p>If you are planning on making your Node-RED installation accessible on your home network (or the web) it is a good idea to secure it with a password, follow the steps below to add the default admin user and custom password to your instance.</p>
<p>First you will need to install the <code>node-red-admin</code> package.</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo npm install -g node-red-admin
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Once installed run the below command making sure to follow the prompts to generate your password hash:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
node-red-admin hash-pw
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Once you have the hashed password we will need to edit Node-RED's <code>settings.js</code> file and enable the admin user account, you can edit the file with the following command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo nano /home/niemandr/.node-red/settings.js
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Find the <code>Securing Node-RED</code> section (shown below) and un-comment the <code>adminAuth</code> section making sure that you replace the default password with the hash generated above.</p>
<img src="./003.png" alt="" />
<p>Next, save and close the configuration file and restart Node-RED (for now you can just run it from the terminal via the node-red command). Once started head over to the Web UI and you should be presented with a login dialog similar to this:</p>
<img src="./004.png" alt="" />
<p>You should be able to now log in using the admin user and your selected password!</p>
<h2 id="create-a-node-red-service">Create a Node-RED Service</h2>
<p>Ideally we want Node-RED to start when the server boots, after some digging online the below process worked best for me (<a href="https://nodered.org/docs/faq/starting-node-red-on-boot">more information here</a>). Basically we are going to install <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/pm2">pm2</a> which is a process manager plugin for Node.js and can be configured to start services on boot.</p>
<h3 id="installing-pm2">Installing pm2</h3>
<p>You can install pm2 using the following command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo npm install -g pm2
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Once installed you will need to get the path to the node-red executable using the which command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
which node-red
{% endhighlight %}

<p>In my case I am using the default Node-RED binary (<code>/usr/bin/node-red</code>).</p>
<p>You can test that everything is working as expected by running the below command (making sure to use the path to your node-red binary):</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
pm2 start /usr/bin/node-red -- -v
{% endhighlight %}

<p>This should start Node-RED in the background, you can view information about the process and access the log output using the commands:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
pm2 info node-red
pm2 logs node-red
{% endhighlight %}

<h3 id="starting-node-red-on-boot">Starting Node-RED on boot</h3>
<p>You can configure Node-RED to start on boot by running the below commands, you will need to have pm2 installed (covered above):</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
pm2 save
pm2 startup systemd
{% endhighlight %}

<p>The last command will output another command that you will need to run in order to configure Node-RED to start up on server reboot, in my case the following output was generated (Note the output may vary for your setup).</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo env PATH=$PATH:/usr/bin /usr/lib/node_modules/pm2/bin/pm2 startup systemd -u niemandr --hp /home/niemandr
{% endhighlight %}

<p>After running the generated command on my server I got confirmation that Node-RED was configured to start on boot:</p>
<img src="./005.png" alt="" />
<p>The only thing left to do now, is to restart the server and see if Node-RED starts by itself, and in my case it did!</p>
<img src="./006.png" alt="" />
<h2 id="fixing-node-red-permissions">Fixing Node-RED permissions</h2>
<p>Presumably you installed Node-RED using your user account (as root is disabled by default on Ubuntu), so you will need to amend some permissions before you can install any additional pallets to Node-RED.</p>
<p>After some digging on Google I came across this post which had an all-in-one command that fixed my permissions perfectly, maybe this will save you some time!</p>
<p>Navigate to your Node-RED folder (in my case it was <code>/home/niemandr/.node-red</code>) and run this command to fix permissions:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo find ~ -type d -user root -exec sudo chown -R $USER: {} +
{% endhighlight %}

<blockquote>
<p><strong>NOTE</strong>: you need to be in your Node-RED directory before running this command!</p>
</blockquote>
<h2 id="installing-palettes">Installing Palettes</h2>
<p>Once you have fixed the permissions (covered above) you should be able to install any palettes normally through Node-RED.</p>
<img src="./007.png" alt="" />
<p>Thanks to the fix above I was able to install all the palettes I needed with no permission errors.</p>
<img src="./008.png" alt="" />
<h2 id="automated-backups">Automated Backups</h2>
<p>As a bonus I thought I would cover creating automated backups of your Node-RED server using a CRON job.</p>
<h3 id="the-zip-command">The zip command</h3>
<p>Node-RED stores all your flows in a file with the flows_<HOST>.json naming convention, in my case that was:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
/home/niemandr/.node-red/flows_<HOST>.json
{% endhighlight %}

<p>I would like to backup this file along with the settings.js file daily. The easiest way I could think of doing this was to make use of the zip command which we will need to first install using:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo apt install zip
{% endhighlight %}

<p>We can simply zip any files matching the <code>*.json</code> pattern in your Node-RED configuration folder (in my case that was <code>/home/niemandr/.node-red</code>) using the below command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
zip "/home/niemandr/Node-RED-$(date '+%F').zip" /home/niemandr/.node-red/*.json
{% endhighlight %}

<p>This will create a zip file with the following naming convention: <code>Node-RED-&lt;DATE&gt;.zip</code>:</p>
<img src="./009.png" alt="" />
<h3 id="creating-the-cron">Creating the CRON</h3>
<p>You can manage your CRON jobs using the below command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
crontab -e
{% endhighlight %}

<p>If this is the first time working with users' CRON jobs you will be prompted to create a new file, if this is the case just use the suggested defaults.</p>
<p>Add the below line to your CRON file (making changes where required):</p>
{% highlight "text" %}
50 20 * * * zip "/home/niemandr/Node-RED-$(date '+\%F').zip" /home/niemandr/.node-red/*.json
{% endhighlight %}

<p>You can use <a href="https://crontab.guru/">this site</a> to help generate a suitable CRON schedule expression, as you can see I have configured mine to run every day at 8:50 pm:</p>
<img src="./010.png" alt="" />
<p>Once done, save and close the CRON file.</p>
<p>You are now configured with daily backups of your Node-RED service!</p>
